An opinion:  Graham Norton is one of the best, if not the best to host. Leaving the details of his show aside, he brings a certain energy to his show which allows for natural emotion and stories to take place. People are encouraged to be themselves, and Norton rarely, if ever, interrupts his guests, and on top of that, he understands comedic timing, and is generally polite and respectable to the people who come on his show, and extends that same energy towards his guests.  Conan did not come across as arrogant, and he slowly but surely evolved as his own process went along. By the end, he even removed the desk and started to get more personal with people. He is a funny guy, and is a good host, but unlike Graham Norton, he is as much a part of the show as anyone else, but he is not above degrading himself, and I believe this also is contributed by his very funny remotes he has done.  Colbert is a good host as well - and much like Jon Stewart, is respectable and can diffuse situations with grace and humor. He doesn't come across as arrogant, and is often unwilling to accept praise. His limitations come from the format of his show, and can across as rather pedantic and slow, but its appeal is in its familiarity and comfort.   Here is where we cross over.   Bill Maher is arrogant. However, he is intelligent, and more than willing to have different perspectives on the show, and his own audience will abandon him or boo him at times. He gets respect for not trying to be popular, and backing up his opinions, but he often interrupts his guests, and certainly has an ego.  Both Jimmy Fallon & Kimmel are unfunny and rather unprofessional. Both embarrass their guests, with Fallon embarrassing himself often as well. Kimmel insults his guests at times, while Fallon is fake with everyone, and neither of them broach anything worth remembering.  Lastly, James. G. Is as unfunny as he is ridiculous. His show might have the least substance of all.   Anyway, I know there are others that are either on the air or have been off for awhile such as Jon Stewart and Ferguson or Carson, etc, but other than Stewart, who was class - I haven't seen too much of them, so I can't properly pose an argument.

It's not necessarily bad, but it foregrounds the host even more and minimizes guest interaction in favor of one on one. You don't get the kind of thing Graham creates every time.
